==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|novice|lang=fro}}, {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|novice|lang=fr}}, borrowed from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|novīcius}}, later {{term|lang=la|novitius||new, newly arrived}} (in Late Latin as a noun, masculine {{term|lang=la|novicius}}, feminine {{term|lang=la|novicia||one who has newly entered a monastery or a convent}}), from {{term|lang=la|novus||new}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈnɒvɪs/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[beginner]]; one who is not very [[familiar]] or [[experienced]] in a particular subject. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''I'm only a '''novice''' at coding, and my programs frequently have bugs that more experienced programmers wouldn't make.''
# {{senseid|en|religious}}{{context|religion|lang=en}} A [[new]] [[member]] of a [[religious]] [[order]] accepted on a [[conditional]] basis, prior to [[confirmation]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1983''', {{w|Lawrence Durrell}}, ''Sebastian'', Faber & Faber 2004 (Avignon Quintet), page 1137:
#*: Nor had it been difficult to find a Coptic priest who, together with his youthful '''novice''', chanted the seemingly interminable Egyptian service of the dead [...].

